        "bach-structure": {
            "id": "bach-structure",
            "summary": "Bach teaches them about the mathematical architecture of music",
            "text": "Bach beckons them to his desk, covered with sheets of complex musical notation. 'Music is mathematics made audible,' he says. 'Listen.'\n\nHe plays a melody on a nearby harpsichord. Then he plays it again, but higher. Then again, with the second version overlapping the first. Then a third voice joins, weaving between the others.\n\n'This is fugue‚Äîmultiple melodies intertwining according to strict rules. Like a conversation where everyone speaks at once, yet somehow it all makes sense.'\n\n{{PLAYER1_NAME}} watches the colored ribbons braid together. 'It looks like math!'\n\n'It is! Music follows patterns. Intervals between notes can be measured. Rhythms divide time precisely. The octave‚Äîwhy does the eighth note sound like a higher version of the first? Because its frequency is exactly double. Physics and poetry combined!'\n\nHe shows them a score. 'My music has been called cold, mathematical. But look closer‚Äîevery rule I follow, I follow to create beauty. Structure is not the enemy of emotion. It is the framework that holds emotion, like a vase holds flowers.'",
