        "bach-practice": {
            "id": "bach-practice",
            "summary": "Bach explains that genius comes from discipline and hard work",
            "text": "'Were you always this good?' {{PLAYER2_NAME}} asks.\n\nBach laughs heartily. 'I had to work very hard. I walked 250 miles once, just to hear a famous organist play. I copied music by candlelight to study it. I practiced until my fingers bled.'\n\n'But you're a genius!'\n\n'Genius is patience. I wrote one piece of music every week for church services‚Äîfor years. Thousands of pieces. Most people only know a few of them now. But every one taught me something. Every one made the next one better.'\n\nHe plays a simple melody, then shows how he would vary it, improve it, transform it into something complex and beautiful.\n\n'Do not wait for inspiration. Work. Inspiration finds those who are already working. If I had waited to feel inspired before composing, I would have written nothing. Instead, I sat down every day, put pen to paper, and trusted that the music would come. And it did.'\n\n{{PLAYER1_NAME}} thinks about practicing piano at home, how boring it sometimes felt. Maybe there's more to it than just playing through pieces.",
