        "mozart-creativity": {
            "id": "mozart-creativity",
            "summary": "Mozart explains how ideas come and how to capture them",
            "text": "'Where do your ideas come from?' {{PLAYER2_NAME}} asks.\n\nMozart tilts his head. 'Everywhere! A bird singing. Raindrops on a window. The rhythm of a horse's hooves. A pretty girl's laugh. Life is full of music‚Äîyou just have to listen.'\n\nHe demonstrates, tapping out a rhythm on the table. 'That's the heartbeat of this room‚Äîcan you hear it? Now add a melody...' He hums. 'Now imagine strings here, a flute there...'\n\n'But how do you remember it all?'\n\n'I don't always!' Mozart laughs. 'Ideas come and go like butterflies. The trick is to catch them quickly.' He shows them a small notebook covered in scribbled notes. 'I write everything down. The good ideas, the bad ones‚Äîyou can't always tell which is which until later.'\n\n{{PLAYER1_NAME}} notices some crossed-out measures. 'Even you make mistakes?'\n\n'Constantly! But here's the secret: mistakes are just ideas that haven't found their right place yet. Something that doesn't work in one piece might be perfect in another. Never throw anything away.'",
