        "beethoven-emotions": {
            "id": "beethoven-emotions",
            "summary": "Beethoven teaches about expressing deep feelings through music",
            "text": "Beethoven's corner is intense. His piano is surrounded by crumpled paper‚Äîdiscarded attempts at perfection. When he plays, the colored ribbons of music are darker, more dramatic than the others.\n\n'Music must strike fire from the heart,' he says, his voice passionate. 'It is not enough to be pretty. It must mean something. It must make you feel.'\n\nHe plays a thunderous passage‚Äî{{BOTH_NAMES}} feel it in their chests. Then soft, tender notes that bring tears to their eyes.\n\n'How do you do that?' {{PLAYER1_NAME}} whispers.\n\n'I do not just play notes. I become the emotion. When I write joy, I feel joy. When I write sorrow, I am drowning in sorrow. The music is true because I am true when I write it.'\n\n{{PLAYER2_NAME}} notices something. 'But you can't hear it anymore?'\n\n'I feel it.' Beethoven places his hand on the piano's soundboard. 'The vibrations tell me what I need to know. And inside my head, the music plays perfectly. Deafness took away sound, but it could not take away music. Music lives deeper than ears.'",
