        "beethoven-deaf": {
            "id": "beethoven-deaf",
            "summary": "Beethoven shares how he overcame deafness through determination",
            "text": "'When I first realized I was going deaf,' Beethoven says quietly, 'I wanted to die. Music was everything to me. How could I live without hearing it?'\n\n{{BOTH_NAMES}} listen, transfixed.\n\n'I wrote a letter saying goodbye, planning to end my life. But then I thought: I have so much music still inside me. The Ninth Symphony wasn't written yet. The late quartets. So much left to say.'\n\nHe plays a hopeful melody. 'I chose to live for my art. I could not hear birds or voices or applause, but I could still create. The music in my mind grew even richer because there was nothing to distract from it.'\n\n{{PLAYER1_NAME}} asks, 'How did you conduct your symphonies without hearing?'\n\n'Very poorly at first!' Beethoven almost smiles. 'I watched the musicians, felt the rhythm, trusted what I had written. At the premiere of my Ninth Symphony, when it ended, I didn't hear the audience cheering. A singer had to turn me around to see them on their feet, weeping with joy. I had given them something true. That mattered more than hearing it myself.'",
