        "ninth-symphony": {
            "id": "ninth-symphony",
            "summary": "They experience Beethoven's Ode to Joy as a visual and auditory wonder",
            "text": "'Would you like to hear my Ninth?' Beethoven asks. Before they can answer, the space around them transforms.\n\nThey're in a vast concert hall. An orchestra materializes‚Äînot playing, waiting. Beethoven raises his arms.\n\nThe music begins. Dark, mysterious. The colored ribbons start as deep purple, almost black. Then themes emerge, develop, clash. For forty minutes, {{BOTH_NAMES}} experience music as they never have before‚Äîseeing it, feeling it, understanding how each section builds on the last.\n\nAnd then‚Äîthe final movement. A human voice sings out the famous 'Ode to Joy' melody. More voices join. The ribbons burst into brilliant gold and white. The message is unmistakable: after struggle, after darkness, after pain‚Äîjoy. Universal, unstoppable joy.\n\nWhen it ends, {{PLAYER2_NAME}} is crying openly. {{PLAYER1_NAME}} feels like {{PLAYER1_HE_SHE}}'s been through a journey.\n\n'That melody,' Beethoven says softly, 'was in my head for twenty years before I used it. I knew it was special. I was saving it for the right moment. The moment when humanity needed to hear that joy is possible even in the darkest times.'",
