        "music-emotions": {
            "id": "music-emotions",
            "summary": "The Muse explains how music directly affects our feelings and bodies",
            "text": "'Why does music make us feel things?' {{PLAYER2_NAME}} asks the Muse.\n\n'Your brain is wired for music,' she explains. 'Scientists have found that music activates almost every area of the brain at once‚Äîmore than any other activity. It triggers memories, emotions, even physical responses.'\n\nShe demonstrates. A minor key plays‚Äîsadness washes over them. Switch to major‚Äîinstant relief, even happiness. Fast tempo‚Äîexcitement. Slow‚Äîcalm.\n\n'But why?' {{PLAYER1_NAME}} persists.\n\n'We don't fully know. Perhaps music mimics the sounds of human emotion‚Äîthe rhythm of an excited heartbeat, the pitch of a voice rising in fear, the resolution of tension when danger passes. Perhaps it's older than language, a way our ancestors communicated before words.'\n\nShe plays a lullaby. Both children feel drowsy. 'Music affects heart rate, breathing, hormone levels. A surgeon uses calming music to relax patients. An athlete uses energizing music to prepare for competition. Stores use music to affect shopping behavior!'\n\n{{PLAYER2_NAME}} laughs. 'Music is like a superpower!'\n\n'It is. Use it wisely.'",
